40|$|This joint U. S. -German {{evaluation}} of seals developed by {{each other is}} part of the U. S. -German bilateral exchange program. The purpose was to arrive at an independent {{evaluation of}} both <b>electronic</b> <b>seal</b> systems and then jointly define the characteristics a next generation <b>electronic</b> <b>seal</b> should possess. The independent evaluations are summarized in this document. Many of the features jointly agreed upon as desirable for a state-of-the art <b>electronic</b> <b>seal</b> are contained in the latest version of the German developed VACOSS 3 system. This system has drawn on the U. S. and German development and evaluation activities in arriving at its present status. The U. S. development activity was completed in 1980 whereas the VACOSS 3 continued incorporating new ideas in early 1983. The joint testing was thus not only for comparison purposes, but also to generally aid in future <b>electronic</b> <b>seal</b> development. Operational testing of both seals revealed a need for improved procedures. Both seals generally met the specified environmental operating conditions. Vulnerability testing identified the ability to predict the code sequences in the older U. S. seal and revealed physical vulnerabilities of the VACOSS 3 system which are being corrected. Our conclusion is that the VACOSS 3 represents the most attractive <b>electronic</b> <b>seal</b> developed to date. It is therefore recommended that the VACOSS 3 be used in the first Agency <b>electronic</b> <b>seal</b> safeguards applications...|$|R
